Title: The impact of asphalt particles on nitrification in reconstructed soils and the role of biome in PAH release
Authors: Elia Biagini, Serena Falcioni, Cecilia Polizzi, Leandro Di Gloria, Matteo Ramazzotti, Giulio Munz, Giacomo Certini

Abstract: 
Urban desealing, aimed at restoring permeable surfaces and enhancing ecosystem services,
generates substantial quantities of waste asphalt. The management of this material through
landfilling represents a significant economic burden that often discourages restoration initiatives. To
address these challenges, the on-site integration of reclaimed asphalt into constructed soils has
been proposed as a circular and cost-effective alternative. This study evaluates the environmental
viability of this practice, investigating whether asphalt triggers adverse effects on soil ecosystems
or the release of hazardous substances. Experimental mixtures with asphalt proportions ranging
from 0% to 50% w/w, amended with 5% compost, were maintained in both liquid and solid phases.
Microbial functionality was assessed by measuring nitrification rates as a functional sentinel,
alongside DNA metagenomics to identify taxonomic shifts. Results showed no acute toxicity to
nitrifying biomass; nitrification rates remained stable across all treatments despite a dose-
dependent decline in sensitive ammonia-oxidizing archaea (AOA). While supernatant PAHs
remained below the limit of quantification (&lt; 0.1 mg/L), solid-phase exceedances for compounds
such as benzo[a]pyrene occurred in asphalt-rich samples (25–50%). DNA sequencing identified
highly diverse communities, with a specialized enrichment of hydrocarbon degraders including
Nocardia and Immundisolibacter. These findings suggest that while high asphalt ratios may
challenge regulatory limits for solid matrices, the functional resilience of the nitrogen cycle and the
strong immobilization of contaminants provided by the compost-soil matrix support the feasibility of
this approach. However, low asphalt-to-soil ratios are advisable to ensure long-term microbial
functionality and environmental safety in urban landscape design.
